{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2e59e36c-d1e4-448f-a0ca-972fa1c8ae4b","content":"Two things changed when you enabled MTP (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`):\n\n1. **`--filter` is now passed through the MTP compatibility layer**, which doesn't support the VSTest `~` (contains) operator or `&` (AND) the same way.\n2. **The native MTP mechanism is `--treenode-filter`**, which uses a glob/path-based syntax.\n\n### Translation\n\n**Old (VSTest / xUnit v2):**\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**New (MTP / xUnit v3) — pass native args after `--`:**\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*/**[Category=Smoke]\"\n```\n\n**How it maps:**\n\n| VSTest concept | MTP tree-node-filter equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` | `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` (glob on the node path) |\n| `Category=Smoke` | `[Category=Smoke]` (property filter on the node) |\n| `&` (AND) | Combining the glob path with `[prop=val]` is an implicit AND |\n\nThe tree-node filter treats tests as a path `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<method>`, so `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` matches any test inside a class whose name contains `IntegrationTests`, and the `[Category=Smoke]` suffix restricts to nodes with that trait.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00dc19d7-0b89-4636-a9a2-8b82cecabef8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with MTP (Microsoft Testing Platform). Let me explain the key differences:\n\n1. **VSTest filter syntax** (`--filter`): `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke`\n   - `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` means \"FQN contains IntegrationTests\"\n   - `&` means AND\n   - `Category=Smoke` matches the `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]`\n\n2. **MTP filter syntax**: When `UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner` is `true`, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform instead of VSTest. \n\nWith MTP, the filtering approach shifts—while `--filter` might still work through a compatibility layer, the native MTP way uses `--treenode-filter` with a path-based syntax like `/**/*IntegrationTests*` instead of the property-based VSTest approach. me think more carefully...\n\nWith `dotnet test` and MTP enabled (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`), the `--filter` option is passed through to MTP. MTP supports the `--treenode-filter` option natively.\n\nActually, the key issue is:\n1. VSTest used `--filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"` with properties like `FullyQualifiedName`, `Category`, etc.\n2. MTP uses `--treenode-filter` with a different path-based syntax.\n\nFor xUnit v3 with MTP:\n- `--treenode-filter` uses a path-like syntax: `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<method>`\n- Traits are expressed differently\n\nIn .NET 9+, when MTP is enabled, `--filter` still works but gets translated through MTP's filter system, and xUnit v3 interprets it differently than VSTest did. The practical solution is to use `--treenode-filter` with path-based patterns like `/**/*IntegrationTests*/**` for class name matching, though trait filtering with MTP requires a different approach than the old VSTest syntax. The tree node filter syntax uses path patterns with glob support and property matching, so a practical example would filter by both the test name pattern and trait properties. The key difference is that `dotnet test --filter` now gets interpreted through MTP's tree node system, where operators like contains work on the hierarchical path structure rather than flat string matching. I should clarify the most direct approach: using `--treenode-filter` after the `--` separator gives the clearest control over what MTP actually filters on. The key insight is that MTP's tree-node filtering uses a different syntax than VSTest's `--filter` flag—path globs combine with property filters in square brackets, so the `FullyQualifiedName` and `&` operators map to glob patterns and `[Category=Smoke]` syntax respectively. Since the user's `--filter` approach isn't working, the native MTP command with `--treenode-filter` is likely the correct path forward.","outputTokens":1857},"id":"5a4ce124-0930-451b-86e9-5b260dd7aa2a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:55:04.685Z","parentId":"dd9143f7-c13c-48f6-9f45-49c2f30223bb"}
